{"actor":{"display":"Evin Tunador","id":"evintunador@gmail.com","type":"human"},"content":{"blocks":[{"content":"55:\n56:## Sharing (transport)\n57:\n58:The ledger travels with normal git use, no extra commands:\n59:\n60:- **Push**: the first capture in a repo installs a `pre-push` hook (chaining\n61:  safely onto any existing shell hook; backing off with a warning when\n62:  `core.hooksPath`/husky owns the hooks). On `git push` it pushes the ledger\n63:  ref alongside, gated by the secret scan. A finding holds back **only the\n64:  ledger** — your code push proceeds — unless you opt into\n65:  `{\"transport\": {\"strict\": true}}`, which aborts the whole push.\n66:- **Fetch**: the same first capture adds a fetch refspec on `origin`, so\n67:  `git fetch`/`git pull` stages teammates' events; any read command\n68:  (`cledger log`, `show`, ...) folds them in via the conflict-free\n69:  `cat_sort_uniq` union. The local ref is never force-overwritten.\n70:- **Opting out**: `{\"transport\": {\"hook\": false, \"fetchRefspec\": false}}` in\n71:  `.cledger.json` or `~/.config/cledger/config.json`, or just delete the\n72:  marked block from `.git/hooks/pre-push`. `cledger sync` always works\n73:  explicitly either way.\n74:\n75:If git has no author identity configured (`user.email` unset), human turns\n76:are recorded unattributed; `cledger install` warns about this. cledger uses\n77:the same identity a commit would be authored under (config or environment)\n78:and never guesses a hostname-based one.\n79:\n80:## Adapters\n81:\n82:Supported today (built-in, hook-based, per-turn):\n83:\n84:| Source | Trigger | Transcript store | Notes |\n85:|---|---|---|---|\n86:| Claude Code CLI | `Stop`/`SessionEnd` hooks | `~/.claude/projects/*/*.jsonl` | Also covers the VS Code extension and JetBrains plugin (both share `~/.claude/settings.json` hooks and transcripts), and desktop-app local/SSH/WSL sessions. Cloud \"Remote\" sessions and the Cowork tab run server-side — not captured. |\n87:| Codex CLI | `[[hooks.Stop]]` hooks engine | `~/.codex/sessions/**/rollout-*.jsonl` | Same config + session store is shared by the Codex desktop app and IDE extension, so their local sessions should capture too — but OpenAI has open bugs on the desktop app's config loading, and third-party reports say hooks may not fire from IDE sessions. Treat non-CLI surfaces as best-effort; `cledger capture codex` backfills any rollout file regardless of which surface wrote it. Cloud tasks run server-side — not captured. Inter-agent messages (`agent_message`) are captured with their visible text; their encrypted blocks are never stored, same policy as reasoning. |\n88:\n89:TODO adapters, roughly in order of how ledger-friendly their storage/hook\n90:story looks (all have local session stores; most grew Claude-Code-style hook\n91:systems):\n92:\n93:- **Gemini CLI** — JSON chats under `~/.gemini/tmp/<hash>/chats/`; documented hooks.\n94:- **Kimi CLI** — `~/.kimi-code/` sessions; Claude-Code-inspired lifecycle hooks.\n95:- **GitHub Copilot CLI** — `~/.copilot/session-state/`; documented hooks dirs.\n96:- **Factory droid** — `~/.factory/` sessions; `hooks.json`.\n97:- **Qwen Code** — `~/.qwen/projects/*/chats/`; hooks system.\n98:- **opencode** — SQLite under `~/.local/share/opencode/`; plugin-API events rather than shell hooks.\n99:- **Cursor (`cursor-agent` CLI)** — `~/.cursor/chats`; hooks exist, but IDE-side chats live in editor-internal storage.\n100:- **aider** — plain `.aider.chat.history.md`; no hook mechanism found, would need file watching.\n101:- **Goose / Amp** — SQLite store / cloud-synced threads; hook stories unclear or absent.\n102:\n103:## Security & redaction\n104:\n105:Visible tool output can contain secrets: API keys in error messages, credentials in logs, etc. The trust boundary is transport — native transcripts are plaintext locally, so redaction protects the *shared* record, not the local disk. Once content reaches a note, removal is expensive, so prevention runs first at capture, with the last checkpoint at sync.\n106:\n107:### Redaction layers\n108:\n109:**Capture-time redaction** (default on): Replaces prefixed tokens (`ghp_…`, `sk-ant-…`, `AKIA…`, `xox…-`, `AIza…`, `glpat-…`, `npm_…`, `sk_live_…`), PEM private keys, JWTs with `[REDACTED:<rule-id>:<fingerprint>]`. Conservative, near-zero false-positive ruleset applied before event ids are computed.\n110:- Threat addressed: API tokens and private keys in tool output land in shared history.\n111:- Cost of disabling: `.cledger.json` `{\"redact\": {\"capture\": false}}` — every secret lands verbatim.\n112:\n113:**Custom patterns**: Extend capture rules via `{\"redact\": {\"patterns\": [{\"id\": \"my-rule\", \"pattern\": \"...\"}]}}` in `~/.config/cledger/config.json` (global) or `<repo>/.cledger.json` (repo wins).\n114:- Threat addressed: domain-specific secrets unmatched by standard rules.\n115:- Cost: manual configuration required.\n116:\n117:**Env-value masking** (opt-in, default off): Scrub exact values of environment variables and `.env` entries via `{\"redact\": {\"env\": true}}`.\n118:- Threat addressed: unstructured secrets in local config.\n119:- Cost of enabling: `.env` plain-config values get masked too; machine-dependent (rescans produce duplicate events with different ids).\n120:\n121:**Known-secret learning** (opt-in, default off): Remember the exact values a `cledger redact <event-id> --pattern` scrubbed, then exact-match them out of every future capture (under a `known-secret` rule id). Enable with `{\"redact\": {\"knownSecrets\": true}}`. Confirmed values are stored locally under `.git/conversation-ledger/known-secrets.json`, written owner-only (`0600`) — never tracked or pushed by git, the same tier as the allowlist. Only `--pattern` feeds it; values under 8 chars are never remembered.\n122:- Threat addressed: the capture/scan feedback loop — a value the broad sync scan catches but the conservative capture tier misses gets re-ingested raw every time you revisit it while fixing it. Once redacted, capture learns it and it can never be re-captured raw again.\n123:- Cost of enabling: confirmed secret plaintext lives in a new (local, unshared) file; like env masking, capture becomes machine-dependent for those values. Concretely, re-capturing a source line whose value is now remembered yields *scrubbed* content and therefore a different event id, so it no longer dedups against the pre-existing event — you get a second, also-scrubbed copy rather than a resurrected secret. Id churn, not leakage.\n124:\n125:**Sync-time scan** (default on, tiered): Before any push, scans only new events with medium/high-precision rules (capture ruleset re-run, keyword assignments like `password=`, URL credentials). Findings abort the ledger push with a report and remediation instructions; the report shows ~20 chars of surrounding context with the matched value **fully masked** (`<redacted>`, zero secret characters) so the report itself can't re-seed the next scan. In the pre-push hook, a finding holds back only the ledger and lets your code push proceed unless `{\"transport\": {\"strict\": true}}`.\n126:- Threat addressed: secrets from older capture rules or new tool formats slipping through.\n127:- Cost of disabling: `{\"scan\": {\"tier\": \"off\"}}` — secrets in tool output push silently.\n128:- Remediation paths: `cledger redact <event-id>` (real secrets), `cledger allow <fingerprint>` (false positives), `cledger sync --no-scan` (bypass once). `--paranoid` tier adds entropy-based detection (noisier but broader).\n129:\n130:### Commands\n131:\n132:`cledger redact <event-id> (--pattern REGEX | --all) [--reason TEXT]`: Rewrites stored event to placeholder + audit metadata, appends a `redaction` event, and squashes local notes history so prior content is unrecoverable (pre-push only; post-push purge tooling is planned, not yet built).\n133:\n134:`cledger scan [--paranoid]`: Standalone check with exit 1 on findings — CI-friendly.\n135:\n136:#