{"actor":{"id":"claude-fable-5","type":"agent"},"content":{"blocks":[{"text":"Both roadmap edits are in the README (uncommitted — say the word if you want it committed now or bundled with the implementation commits). Now your questions.\n\n**Connecting the patch-id dots, concretely.** Say you branched `feat-x` off main at commit M, made commits A→B→C, and captured conversations along the way (anchored to A, B, C). You open a PR; meanwhile main moves ahead. Someone clicks \"Squash and merge,\" creating commit S on main. Later you `git fetch`. Now the detection pass runs, and it has two things in hand: locally it still has `feat-x` (M, A, B, C), and it just received S. It computes one diff for \"everything the branch did\" (`git diff M..C`), and one diff for \"everything S did\" (`git diff S^..S`), pipes each through `git patch-id`, and compares the two fingerprints. Main having moved doesn't matter, because we're comparing the *changes*, not the snapshots — and if GitHub applied the branch cleanly, the changes are byte-identical. Match → append the mapping event \"A, B, C superseded by S\" anchored to S. For a rebase-merge it's the same trick per commit: fingerprint A, B, C individually, fingerprint each of the three new commits on main, and pair them up. That per-commit pairing also covers your scenario (b), a bot rewriting your pushed commits — a rewrite that preserves the change matches; one that alters it falls through to the suggestion tier. And yes, (a) and (b) are both real issues; (c) was the non-issue.\n\n**Is any of this GitHub-specific?** The core isn't: patch-id matching is pure local git and works identically no matter where the squash happened — GitHub, GitLab, Gitea, a coworker's laptop. Only the *evidence/metadata* layer is forge-specific, and every forge has an analogue: GitHub squash subjects end in `(#123)`, GitLab merge commits say `See merge request !123`, Gitea/Forgejo follow GitHub's convention. So your instinct is exactly right and I wrote the roadmap items that way: a small forge abstraction (three capabilities: \"what PR/MR is this branch?\", \"what does a squash message look like here?\", \"fetch the discussion\") with GitHub as the only initial driver. Core detection never depends on it; the forge layer only upgrades suggestion quality.\n\n**How does the TUI know your branch's PR?** Git itself has no idea — a PR is a forge-side database row, not a git object. The `gh` CLI (which Claude Code shells out to) asks GitHub's API \"any open PRs whose head branch is `feat-x` on this repo?\" And yes, we should use that window: while the PR is *open*, a cheap `gh` lookup lets us cache \"branch `feat-x` = PR #123, title so-and-so\" under `.git/conversation-ledger/` (rebuildable local state, allowed by the design rules). When a squash appears later with `(#123)` in its subject, the fuzzy case stops being fuzzy — we expected exactly that number. It stays confirm-don't-assume for anything patch-id can't verify, but the confirmation prompt becomes near-certain instead of speculative. Degrades gracefully when `gh` is absent or the forge isn't GitHub.\n\n**Your reproducibility tool is probably fine — with one caveat.** Git's GC never deletes branches; only humans and forges delete branches. GC deletes *objects* (commits and their file snapshots) that nothing points to anymore. A \"headless\" commit hash stays fully restorable as long as *any* ref reaches it — a branch, a tag, anything — indefinitely. The danger case is precisely the one we've been discussing: the commit's branch gets deleted (or rebased away) and no other ref reaches it; then it survives only on reflog grace periods (roughly 2 weeks–3 months by default) before pruning. So: if your tool restores commits that live on kept branches or tags, it's sound. If it might be pointed at commits from deleted/rebased branches, it's quietly time-bombed — and the fix is one line at snapshot time: create a ref to pin the commit, ideally in a hidden namespace like `refs/snapshots/<name>` so it doesn't clutter `git branch`/`git tag` output. A pinned commit is immortal.\n\n**PR adapter skepticism** — you're right, and I logged it with that skepticism baked in: the *storage* slots in perfectly (a review comment is just a turn with a human actor), but the *adapter shape* doesn't — our current adapters are \"tail a local transcript file with a cursor,\" and this one is \"poll a remote API with auth.\" The roadmap entry says exactly that so nobody later pretends it's a drop-in.\n\n**CI/GitHub App** — added to the roadmap too, because it's more than convenience: an Action running at merge time doesn't have to *detect* the squash at all — it's standing right there when it happens, knows the branch, the PR, and the new SHA, and can append the mapping event with zero inference. It's the eventual clean solution to \"squashes happen off-machine\"; the fetch-side detection we're building is the version that works with no forge setup, and both write the same mapping event.\n\nThat's every concern addressed, I think. The design itself didn't move: mapping event anchored to the squash commit, patch-id as the primary matcher, forge metadata as confirm-tier evidence only. Ready to start on step 1 (mapping event kind + read-time resolution, with tests) whenever you are.","type":"text"}],"role":"assistant"},"context":{"branch":"main","cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","head":"5581e317b1b9c3ea88c5d9dd25808a10fcfc7518","repo":"git@github.com:evintunador/conversation-ledger.git"},"conversation":{"id":"claude-code:4c1ed024-2edf-45b6-8cbb-ee40a5ebadc3","seq":108},"id":"ev1-0ec21c514b28884a71757f049520ce2dcfa7d9e0080aaadced43449b42dcc637","kind":"conversation_turn","occurred_at":"2026-07-21T06:07:57.621Z","producer":{"session_id":"4c1ed024-2edf-45b6-8cbb-ee40a5ebadc3","source":"claude-code","tool":"cledger","version":"0.8.0"},"raw":{"data":{"cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","effort":"high","ent