{"actor":{"id":"claude-fable-5","type":"agent"},"content":{"blocks":[{"text":"Done — re-anchor is fully implemented as 0.8.0, in four commits on `main` (not pushed; say the word). All 125 tests pass, including 13 new ones, and I smoke-tested the CLI end to end in a scratch repo: capture on a branch, simulate a GitHub-style squash with the target branch having drifted, and `cledger log` on main shows the branch's conversation after re-anchoring.\n\nWhat shipped, per commit:\n\n1. **`d3934db` — the mapping primitive.** A new `re_anchor` event kind asserting \"these commits were superseded by this one.\" It's an ordinary append-only event anchored to the squash commit, with deterministic identity (sorted SHAs, `system` actor, the squash commit's own timestamp as `occurred_at`) so two machines detecting the same squash produce byte-identical events that merge into one. Read-time reachability resolves mappings to a fixpoint, so a squash commit that later gets squashed again still resolves through the chain.\n\n2. **`c36b4b5` — detection.** For each local branch the remote default branch no longer contains: tree equality catches a squash of an unmoved target, and `git patch-id` over zero-context diffs catches squashes past unrelated drift plus per-commit rebase/bot rewrites. It runs automatically inside every read after a fetch (the \"plain `git fetch` + `cledger log` just works\" flow the docs wanted), gated on a cursor so it only fires when the remote branch actually moved, and it can never fail a read. Exact matches only — a change matching two commits is reported as ambiguous, never guessed. Opt out with `{\"reanchor\": {\"auto\": false}}`.\n\n3. **`a452048` — the command** (and the 0.8.0 version tick). `cledger re-anchor` is a dry run by default, `--apply` acts, and `cledger re-anchor <old-rev...> --onto REV` handles what matching can't assert — maintainer-edited squashes, deleted branches, ambiguity — recorded with you as the actor. Full 40-char SHAs are accepted even after the old commits are garbage-collected, since the mapping is exactly how an orphaned note stays meaningful.\n\n4. **`5581e31` — docs.** The design doc's \"known limitation: squash merges\" section became the re-anchoring design section; the README got a user-facing section, the roadmap edits from earlier (purge hard-parts, the two forge items), and the re-anchor item marked shipped with the forge-metadata suggestion tier listed as remaining.\n\nOne judgment call to flag: for the maintainer-edited-squash case, nothing is auto-applied and there's no PR-metadata evidence ranking yet — the command just names the branch as ambiguous/unmatched and points at `--onto`. The evidence-ranked confirm flow is written up as the remaining work under the forge abstraction, per our earlier discussion.","type":"text"}],"role":"assistant"},"context":{"branch":"main","cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","head":"5581e317b1b9c3ea88c5d9dd25808a10fcfc7518","repo":"git@github.com:evintunador/conversation-ledger.git"},"conversation":{"id":"claude-code:4c1ed024-2edf-45b6-8cbb-ee40a5ebadc3","seq":388},"id":"ev1-279c9a0cbd77a542123948acd24e6d4020ea9586d40ec03d103ce75d49694926","kind":"conversation_turn","occurred_at":"2026-07-21T06:36:17.707Z","producer":{"session_id":"4c1ed024-2edf-45b6-8cbb-ee40a5ebadc3","source":"claude-code","tool":"cledger","version":"0.8.0"},"raw":{"data":{"cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","effort":"high","entrypoint":"cli","gitBranch":"main","isSidechain":false,"message":{"content":[{"text":"Done — re-anchor is fully implemented as 0.8.0, in four commits on `main` (not pushed; say the word). All 125 tests pass, including 13 new ones, and I smoke-tested the CLI end to end in a scratch repo: capture on a branch, simulate a GitHub-style squash with the target branch having drifted, and `cledger log` on main shows the branch's conversation after re-anchoring.\n\nWhat shipped, per commit:\n\n1. **`d3934db` — t